    <article>
        <articleInfo lang="EN" FirstPage="89" LastPage="120">
            <pdf>26206-jdecp-shevchuk.pdf</pdf>
            <abstract>We propose a reaction-diffusion model for post-infarction myocardial remodeling
                with five tissue states: healthy myocardium, inflammatory infiltrate, necrosis,
                replacement fibrosis, and interstitial fibrosis. The state variables are the
                concentration parameters of a Dirichlet distribution, which makes it possible
                to describe both the mean tissue composition and the uncertainty in transition
                zones. For the resulting quasilinear parabolic system with anisotropic diffusion,
                we establish uniform ellipticity of the diffusion tensor, local Lipschitz
                continuity of the reaction operator, global existence of nonnegative weak
                solutions, invariance of the admissible region, an exponential lower bound,
                and uniqueness under additional regularity. For an auxiliary reversible
                transition matrix, we derive an entropy balance, while for the irreversible
                matrix we obtain a spectral stability condition for the linearized system.
                For the Lie splitting scheme, we state positivity conditions and an error
                estimate in the smooth regime. Numerical examples reproduce
                the standard phase ordering of post-infarction remodeling and provide a basis
                for a subsequent inverse problem driven by LGE-MRI data.</abstract>
            <title>Reaction-diffusion Model of Post-infarction Myocardial Remodeling</title>
            <keywords>
                <word>anisotropic diffusion</word>
                <word>Dirichlet concentration parameters</word>
                <word>entropy balance</word>
                <word>global existence</word>
                <word>inverse problem</word>
                <word>myocardial fibrosis</word>
                <word>quasilinear parabolic system</word>
                <word>uniqueness under additional regularity</word>
            </keywords>
