    <article>
        <articleInfo lang="EN" FirstPage="153" LastPage="165">
            <pdf>26209-jdecp-kuznetsov.pdf</pdf>
            <abstract>Multistability may occur in mechanical systems of various types, when several attractors coexist in the phase space of a model, including periodic and chaotic ones.
                The analysis of multistability is related to the study of global stability boundaries and hidden attractors.
                While a number of effective approximate analytical methods have been developed for detecting periodic attractors in discontinuous models, the analysis of chaotic attractors often relies on numerical investigations.
                This paper studies chaotic attractors and multistability in the mechanical Keldysh model of flutter suppression with a nonlinear discontinuous damper characteristic. To detect chaos, several numerical indicators are used: the 0-1 test, the largest local finite-time Lyapunov exponent, and the ConDN indicator, computed using artificial-intelligence techniques based on reservoir computing with conceptors.
                In addition, the dynamics of the original discontinuous model and its smooth approximation are compared.
                The obtained results reveal new sets of parameters of the Keldysh model for which multistability with chaotic attractors is observed in the phase space, and emphasize the need to develop analytical--numerical methods for chaos analysis in order to estimate global stability boundaries in nonlinear discontinuous mechanical models.</abstract>
            <title>On the Analysis of Chaotic Dynamics in the Keldysh Model</title>
            <keywords>
                <word>AI-assisted analytical-numerical procedures</word>
                <word>chaotic attractors</word>
                <word>discontinuous systems</word>
                <word>flutter suppression</word>
                <word>hidden oscillations</word>
                <word>Keldysh model</word>
                <word>Lyapunov exponents</word>
                <word>multistability</word>
            </keywords>
            <references>
